          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Notes and thoughts from blog <fr:link href="/gaoDiffusionMeetsFlow2024/" title="Diffusion Meets Flow Matching: Two Sides of the Same Coin" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/gaoDiffusionMeetsFlow2024/" display-uri="gaoDiffusionMeetsFlow2024" type="local">Diffusion Meets Flow Matching: Two Sides of the Same Coin</fr:link>. As a useful pre-requisite, I recommend my notes on <fr:link href="/007T/" title="Diffusion Models" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/007T/" display-uri="007T" type="local">diffusion</fr:link> and <fr:link href="/008A/" title="Flow Matching: What, Why, and How?" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008A/" display-uri="008A" type="local">flow matching</fr:link> respectively.</html:p><html:p>To start, I began looking into this due to the wildly empirical claims from <fr:link href="/lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023/" title="Flow Matching for Generative Modeling" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023/" display-uri="lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023" type="local">Flow Matching for Generative Modeling</fr:link>. Namely,</html:p>
 <html:blockquote class="jms-quote" style="
  margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
  padding: 0.6em 1.1em 0.6em 1.3em;
  border-left: 4px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.25);
  border-radius: var(--radius);
  background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.035);
  font-style: italic;
  color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.85);
  ">
  <html:ul><html:li><html:em>"We find that using FM provides more robust and stable training, and achieves superior performance compared to score matching."</html:em></html:li>
   <html:li><html:em>"Furthermore, we find that our models produce better trade-offs between computational cost and sample quality."</html:em></html:li></html:ul>
 </html:blockquote>
